Harry Potter's literary magic
In Princeton – – this summer, at literary festivals and bookstores around the world, readers are commemorating the 20th anniversary of J·K·Rowling's Harry Potter series novel, the first one – – Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) – –. They have a good reason to hold the commemoration.
Since he first appeared on June 26, 1997, this young wizard has become a symbol of "tenacious endurance"
In the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into over 70 languages, and a total of 450 million copies have been released.
The eight films based on this book have earned a total of $70 billion, and Harry Potter theme toys and merchandise have generated another $70 billion in revenue.
It's hard for people with a literary mind and a certain age to imagine that there was a time when the global audience was not fascinated by Rowling's works.
Every time I think back to my students' poor reaction to "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" in the fall of 1999, I am still surprised, for I had included the book in the syllabus of my popular literature course at Princeton University. I had been teaching the "American Bestseller" series since 1993.
The course studies bestsellers from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to ponder why and how these bestsellers attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final work that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Potter fever fiercely attacked the American coast.
On June, the American publisher of the series rushed to release the hardcover edition of the second book in the series, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, to the stores.
The same institution also published the third book in the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had taken the top three spots on the New York Times bestselling novel list, and the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone had topped the paperback bestseller list.
Even Time magazine featured this bespectacled wizard on its cover.
Sightseeing spots of Harry Potter can be seen everywhere.
My students are eager to know what drives this craze.
Good heavens, they're thoroughly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series is nothing but second-rate nonsense, and it can't even hold a candle to their cherished childhood memories of the Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings series.
Although their childhood has only just passed, they, like many infamous adult critics, have been damning Harry Potter as "fabricated", "poor writing", "clichés", and "tedious".

In their view, Harry was neither a miracle nor wise and warm.
Students' negative reactions surprised me, but looking back, it wasn't that astonishing.
Although adults made up a large part of Harry Potter's audience from the beginning, these students were in the wrong age to objectively recognize the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were too old to accept new children's books, but also too young to have their own children (I had just had a child at the time) , and they were eager to believe that although Harry's series is very popular now, it will soon be forgotten.
Second year autumn, that is 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as the final analysis work, just like their peers before, they confidently rejected this work.
Let's fast forward to the spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for a few years, I taught "American Bestseller" again.
When students choose the final analysis work, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works when they were not university students, but rather teenagers just entering their teenage years. This means that they grew up with Harry, Ron, and Hermione as companions.
It happened again in the autumn of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry disappear from memory?
Only as long as we are still alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught the bestseller course twice, and both times, my students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final comments.
Are they tired of Potter?
This is unlikely based on the comments from "Children's Literature" class where students read the Harry series.
Now, I choose to put a Harry Potter novel into the curriculum, but I didn't choose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone", instead I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" --- it's my favorite novel in the Harry Potter series, marking the transition from children's literature to young adult novels, with complex descriptions of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and mercy.
My many students also love this book the most.
But how can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Each time I teach children's literature, I have to conduct a public opinion poll first: "Which of the books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban".
By 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But the percentages continued to decline after that – 87% in 2014, and 81% in 2016.
These are all anecdotal, I know.
But I'm curious: next spring when I teach children's literature again, will the percentage of those who have read Harry Potter be below 80%?
Will the fact prove that the students in 1999-2000 were right: Harry Potter's status is constantly declining, and it will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a turning point ahead, and the percentage will stabilize and not decline further?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am happy to have invited him to my classroom.
